  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT321-kilavi">tōḻi kiḻattikku notumalar varaiyumiṭattu “aṟattoṭu niṟpēṉ” eṉṟatu, </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">The confidante saying to HER “I will stand firm in
          duty”, when strangers [want to] marry [her]. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT321">
          <l> malaicceñ cānti ṉāra mārpiṉaṉ</l>
          <l> cuṉaippūṅ kuvaḷaic curumpār kaṇṇiya</l>
          <l> ṉaṭunāḷ vantu nammaṉaip peyaru</l>
          <l> maṭavara larivainiṉ mārpama riṉṟuṇai</l>
          <l> maṉṟa maraiyā viriya vēṟaṭṭuc</l>
          <l> ceṅka ṇirumpuli kuḻumu mataṉāṉ</l>
          <l> maṟaittaṟ kālaiyō vaṉṟē</l>
          <l> tiṟappal vāḻivēṇ ṭaṉṉainaṅ katavē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>He with a chest full of red sandal paste from the mountains,</l>
          <l>he with a chaplet full of bees from waterlilies,</l>
          <l rend="indent8">flowers from the mountain pool,</l>
          <l>is coming at midnight [and] returning from our house,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">o inexperienced young woman,</l>
          <l rend="indent6">the dear companion who resides in your chest. <note place="foot"> This phrase is difficult because <term xml:lang="ta"> mārpu </term> is usually a designation of the male chest (the female breast is called <term xml:lang="ta">  mulai </term> or <term xml:lang="ta"> ākam </term>). T.V.G., however, brings forth a single parallel from the Kalittokai (18.1f.) for <term xml:lang="ta"> mārpu </term> in the sense of female chest, and Cām. glosses amar here by <term xml:lang="ta"> poruntum </term>, i.e. "the dear companion fit for your chest." An alternative is to read <term xml:lang="ta"> amar </term> as a verbal root, with a parallel in KT 56.5: <term xml:lang="ta"> neñc' amarntōḷē </term>. </note> </l>
          <l>Having killed the bull</l>
          <l rend="indent4">so that the wild cows retreat to the village common</l>
          <l>the red-eyed dark tiger is roaring.<note place="foot"> Up to line 7 any particle marking is missing, and so it seems reasonable to take <term xml:lang="ta"> peyarum </term> and <term xml:lang="ta"> kuḻumum </term> as main predicates. This way of construing has the disadvantage of assembling two disparate vocatives in one poem − the first addressing HER and the second the mother. </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent9">Therefore,</l>
          <l>[is this] a time for hiding? No!</l>
          <l>I will open – oh mother, please  –  <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> vāḻi aṉṉai vēṇṭu: vēṇṭu </term> as an entreating imperative has parallels in NA 351.5 and AN 190.6, while <term xml:lang="ta"> vāḻi </term> is certainly meant as no more than a respectful address here.  </note> our door.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
